<br>
 Actually, as you must know, the technology to go to the Moon did exist and therefore requires no breakthroughs but rather money and a little time. Bush's plan will be unlikely to succeed because its goal is pushed too far beyond his Presidency and because it is not bold enough. Kennedy's speech made even the most enthusiastic gasp when he said ...&quot;Before this decade is out...&quot;.<br>
 Bush in effect said: We will go to the Moon not because it is hard, but because it is relatively easy and if we spread the spending out for a long enough period I can get credit for that vision thing without any real cost. <br>
 The Russians can send you into space for 20 million so I would argue that the access to space problem is already solved to the extent required for exploration. No American launch system developed by NASA will get close to this untill more advanced tech is developed. Apollo succeeded in getting us to the Moon, but it failed in giving us cheap access. Going back to that tech cannot possibly succeed.<br>
 The chances of this leading to flight hardware that changes the status quo is rather remote so it is rather meaningless to speak of private vs. public development. <br>
 Let's go forward to the future not back to the Sixties!<br>
 Steve Mickler <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 275<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/16/04 3:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=993.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What It Is About</span><hr size=1> <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Cheap is dead in space...bud !!!<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
In principle, I agree, However…<br>
<br>
Space is expensive, not so much because the demanding nature of the technology (which it undoubtedly is) but because of the lack of mass production techniques.<br>
<br>
The triumph of 20th century industrial ingenuity is the ability to manufacture fantastically complex and sophisticated pieces of equipment for CENTS per unit or even less!<br>
<br>
I would not be surprised if there is more processing power in a high end PC graphics card than there was on the entire planet in 1969, and its yours for $200! (At the factory gate it is probably less than $20!).<br>
<br>
Why does the military have $1000 toilet seats? ‘Cos they are hand made, one at a time!<br>
<br>
Yesterday I was visiting a customer at his place of work. He is a “Metal basher”, He was making parts for Eurofighter, The part in question was a small section of tapered channel (a bit like a section of car bumper/fender) about 18” long. If you bought it as a Ford bodywork part it would probably cost $5!<br>
<br>
Because this is a Eurofighter part and hand made (also crack tested etc), he can only make 3 to 4 a week, the cost at the factory gate is probably not less than $2500 each.<br>
<br>
I found the following article intriguing, (particularly the astonishingly low marginal production cost on 5000+), Perhaps the author is correct and that this is the way to go, perhaps this is the best way to use public money to kickstart private investment..<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.fourmilab.ch/documents/rocketaday.html" target="top">www.fourmilab.ch/documents/rocketaday.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
