I'm sorry, I'll listen to Freeman Dyson, Ray Bradbury, Pournelle, Walker and others who don't have a political stake in spending lots of money but have the heart to accept minimal risks and the sense to build something to do a purpose, instead of to spend lots of money, before I'll listen to a government bureaucrat in this (likening the money cannon approach to their operating paradigm). <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A> at: 1/17/04 6:54 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 477<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/17/04 6:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=993.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Problems with Shrub's plan</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; Along with retiring the shuttle fleet, the new plan calls<br>
&gt;for NASA to convert a planned follow-on spacecraft<br>
&gt;-- called the orbital space plane -- into versions of a<br>
&gt;new spaceship called the crew exploration vehicle.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I'll shut up about this when I see something technical about it from engineers, instead of Shrub's PR flacks. It just sounds too cheesy like those plans to use the Shuttle for flying to the Moon. &quot;Hey! We've got this thing, so let's make it do a thousand different things to save money!&quot;<br>
<br>
It's like so much of this &quot;plan&quot;; made by white house aids and staffers with no real understanding of space travel beyond the tabloids and TV -parts of it are so dumb and lacking any understanding of space that Shrub himself could haave dreamed it up (IQ ~85).<br>
Kennedy didn't say that we'd use this particular kind of mission infrastructure; for all we knew at the time, it'd be a rendesvous in LEO by several tens of tons lifted, and then the ship goes there.<br>
The White House doesn't design mission architecture, and we've seen nothing realistic that says that these hardware choices came from engineers.<br>
<br>
And let's get this straight from the start: having something on the Moon -even pure refined fuels just sitting there waiting for us to get it- doesn't help us in getting to Mars. It makes no sense to take off from the Moon, it makes no sense to get fuels there, it's nothing like a step on the way to make it easier to go to Mars or anywhere but Luna.<br>
<br>
The main thing that bugs me about this plan is the short-sighted step of completely killing the STS infrastructure. That means we've got no HLV except things like Atlas and Arianne-5 -until we entrust NASA managers with several tens of billion$ to make up their dream vehicle, setting us back 30 years more in a useful, robust, and relatively cheap way to get payloads up.<br>
<br>
 More short duration tentative steps onto the Moon, because we have to use existing rockets without heavy throw-weight, while they tear down all the infrastructure used to build &amp; fly the STS all these years.<br>
 It's just a continuation of the Shuttle Cult (name coined by H.Hickham) which says the Shuttles are the only game in town for doing things in space. We cut it, so we have no choice but to fall back on other smaller things, while we dream of having a space truck.<br>
<br>
If I were the emperor of the world (like Shrub dreams of being), I'd kill involvement in the ISS as it is now, while instigating a crash program to build a Shuttle-C variant to bring up useful big volumes to make it something useful, including maybe a spaceport, if it's in a decent orbit -move it if it's not. The time and money spent on this can't possibly be more than using the Golden Goose to finish it as a tinker toy little thing.<br>
<br>
Do robotic missions to the Moon while designing other Shuttle-C payloads for a manned landing, if we really want to go there this soon, but do others to NEAs ASAP.<br>
If we want some infrastructure in space to help with interplanetary misions, it's got to be an NEA fuel station -which you can't do on the Moon without a drastically higher up-front cost.<br>
<br>
When a rocket carries up a load to LEO, bound for GEO or interplanetary space (and this includes Mars Direct and anything else going there), some 45% of the mass we've placed into LEO is the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">oxidiser</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> in the upper stage</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->...<br>
This means that we need ASAP a source of fuels in LEO, and the only reasonable way to get this is to go to an NEA.<br>
Forget everything but ices. Our first big manned shot beyond LEO is to an NEA, carrying only the first stuff needed to establish itself (power and power conditioning, waste heat venting, and O2 trickle supply.<br>
 Later shots from a Shuttle-C (and we get 3 launch windows a year to an NEA, with much more cargo to an NEA than to the Moon) build this up, so we can bring back bags of ices to LEO. Mars direct or Semi-Direct missions can then carry that much more cargo up to LEO, since the fuels for TMI burns and capture around Mars is waiting for them.<br>
<br>
It's vastly more profitable (in terms of return on the risk) to go to an NEA if we want something other than Lunar science. Vastly less intense rocketry to go there, more cargo delivered, much better resources.<br>
Many of these NEAs are extinct comet cores tugged into the inner solar system. This means that under the surface several meters of regolith, they're soft chunks of ices -nearly 40% by mass in some cases. No prospecting; just set down and dig. no nuclear reactors for the long Lunar night during which they can't work (not that they're bad in themselves, they're just massive and complex compared to foil mirror for an early mission)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.neofuel.com">neofuel.com<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://neofuel.com/markmaxwell/maxwell-mark-icetanker3.5.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
I dont have anything against going back to the Moon, even small steps to start, but to &quot;design&quot; a &quot;plan&quot; that requires going there to &quot;pave the way to Mars&quot; is brainless. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A> at: 1/17/04 6:56 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cotopaxi@nuclearspace>cotopaxi</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 164<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/17/04 9:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=993.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Problems with short sighted BEAN COUNTERS</span><hr size=1> It never ceases to amaze me how many people seem to rally to arguments that short change the effort to get space accessible to exploration and humans.<br>
