XCOR aerospace is my favorite example.  They built their first major piece of operational hardware, a rocketplane, for less than half a million dollars.  That's right... they built a rocketplane for 500k.  That's pennies in the aerospace industry.  Their suborbital vehicle is almost finished, and its total costs including final testing will be about 12 million.  Again... that's for a vehicle capable of launching mini-sats into leo and taking tourists up for rides out of the atmosphere.  The're bootstrapping themselves by doing research and hardware construction contracts for a variety of other companies that apply to the work they're doing.  They do not require the huge 'chunk' investments described in that article.<br>
<br>
On another note,<br>
I think that the dismantling of the shuttle program is one of the best things that could happen.  It'll allow private companies to compete to construct a replacement, and they'll KNOW what the market is, in that there is copious data about shuttle launch costs and demand.  <br>
<br>
It's a great opportunity for private industry to step up and replace the government service with a cheaper and more efficient solution.  I hope they take advantage of it.<br>
